<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n34003b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n34" href="#n34003b">N34 (VI.B.27)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n34all.htm#n34003b"> 3(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Censura Orientalis / Ecclesiae</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The Reformation of the 16th century was not without effect on the Eastern Church. Some of the Reformers, notably Melanchthon, expected to effect a reunion of Christendom by means of the Easterns, cherishing the same hopes as the modern Old Catholic divines and their English sympathizers. &hellip; some years afterwards Jacob Andreae and Martin Crusius began a correspondence with Jeremiah, patriarch of Constantinople, in which they asked an official expression of his opinions about Lutheran doctrine. The result was that Jeremiah answered in his <i><mark>Censura Orientalis Ecclesiae</mark></i> condemning the distinctive principles of Lutheranism. <small> &ldquo;ORTHODOX EASTERN CHURCH&rdquo; <a name="EBOEC" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBOEC"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 335 [Doctrines and Creeds]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
